</P>
<P>
CHINA ADDS SECURITY ON KEY ANNIVERSARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China increased security patrols and virtually sealed off Tibet on the first 
anniversary of the imposition of martial law. 
</P>
<P>
Travel agents in Chengdu, China's main gateway to Lhasa, the Tibetan capital, 
said tours have been canceled and that travel permits will not be issued until 
March 15. Despite the tension, there were no reports of renewed protests by 
Tibetan nationalists. Authorities did allow Tibet's Buddhist monks to continue 
a major prayer festival that has been the occasion of anti-Chinese protests in 
the past. The 10-day festival, which began last week, provoked last year's 
anti-Beijing riots that led to martial law. 
</P>
