<P>
GAF Settles Charges: GAF Corp. agreed to pay $1.25 million plus interest into a 
fund for investors to settle SEC charges that it manipulated the price of Union 
Carbide Corp. stock in 1986. The chemicals manufacturer and its vice chairman, 
James T. Sherwin, did not admit or deny allegations in the civil complaint. 
Sherwin and the company were to be sentenced today in New York for their 
conviction on criminal stock manipulation charges. 
