<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND; 
</P>
<P>
IRS AGENT FOILS KIDNAP ATTEMPT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Two men who stuffed a woman into a North Hollywood trash dumpster during a 
kidnaping and apparent robbery attempt ran off when an Internal Revenue Service 
agent heard her screams and shot at them, Los Angeles police said today. 
</P>
<P>
The woman, a 44-year-old Van Nuys resident whose name was not released, was 
bruised and frightened but otherwise uninjured after the 8:15 p.m. incident 
Thursday, Police Lt. Ron La Rue said. 
</P>
<P>
The two suspects escaped. 
</P>
<P>
John Everett, an agent with the IRS criminal investigation division in Los 
Angeles, was conducting surveillance work in the vicinity of Hesby Drive and 
Lankershim Boulevard when he heard screams coming from the parking lot of the 
Security Pacific bank at the corner. Everett ran to the parking lot and saw 
that two men had put a woman into a trash dumpster and were closing the lid on 
her, La Rue said. 
</P>
<P>
The IRS agent identified himself and fired his handgun at the two men. They 
jumped into a nearby car and fled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA030990-0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 187272 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 9, 1990, Friday, P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part P; Page 2; Column 1; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
94 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
JAPAN AGAIN CAN CALL CAMBODIA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Telephone service from Japan to Cambodia resumed today after a 15-year cutoff, 
according to KDD, Japan's largest international telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
Service, which is routed through Moscow, will be available 24 hours a day, but 
customers will have to wait an average of one to two hours after placing their 
calls through an operator, a KDD official said. 
</P>
<P>
Calls will cost $19 for the first three minutes and $3.20 for each extra 
minute, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Telecommunication service between Japan and Cambodia was cut near the end of 
the Vietnam War in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
