<HEADLINE>
<P>
HUGHES ADMITS THAT CLASSIFIED DATA WAS OBTAINED ILLEGALLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ALEXANDRIA, Va. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hughes Aircraft Co. today pleaded guilty to two felony counts of unlawfully 
obtaining classified Pentagon budget documents and agreed to pay more than 
$3.55 million to settle the case. 
</P>
<P>
Hughes is the fourth major defense contractor to plead guilty through a plea 
bargain to similar charges under an investigation begun in the mid-1980s by the 
Defense Criminal Investigative Service, the investigative arm of the defense 
inspector general. 
</P>
<P>
The two counts concern five-year defense program documents issued in 1983 and 
1984 summarizing resources planned, programmed and budgeted by the Department 
of Defense. 
</P>
<P>
The three other major defense contractors that previously pleaded guilty to 
similar charges are GTE Government Systems Division, which paid about $300,000; 
Boeing, which paid $5.2 million, and RCA Corp., which paid $2.5 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
